Volumes in  docker

10 October 2025
21:10

	Q. Container got crashed or down or deleted, so wt will happen to ur app?

	Ø App will not work means users unable to access the app
	Ø The data will be lost: - files , folders, any imp info


Why volume ?
============

	Ø To persisting the data
	Ø To back up the data


Wt is volume?
============

	Ø Volume is  nothing but it’s a directory 
	Ø You are going to declaring a directory as a volume
	Ø You can share one volume with no.of containers
	Ø You have to create or define a volume along with container.
	Ø Once container got created its difficult to attach a volume to the container
	Ø If any container got deleted still your volume will be there .
	Ø Volume will not be included along with ur image 
	Ø Volume is going to creating out of the file system.


Types of volumes 
==============

	Ø Docker has 3 type of volumes

	1. Anonymous volume:- it means you are not going to assign a meaningful name , using id 
	2. Named volume :- we can assign a name to the volume
	3. Bind volume:-

How to share one volume with one container to another container
=======================================================

docker run -it --name d2  --privileged --volumes-from d1 ubuntu /bin/bash

 --privileged: -it is nothing but you are going to giving authorization to d2 to access the volume
--volumes-from:- d1